{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011Q3kbZH8TEGTWB7Jzz2Tou","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is:\n1. The readiness probe is failing because the replica set hasn't been initialized yet - `ReadConcernMajorityNotAvailableYet: Read concern majority reads are currently not possible.` and `NotYetInitialized: Replication has not yet been configured`.\n2. The StatefulSet is waiting for pod-0 to be ready before creating pods 1 and 2 (this is the default ordinal ordering behavior).\n3. The `ping` command times out because the probe uses a 1s default timeout.\n\nThe main issue is: with a replica set that hasn't been initialized, MongoDB won't respond to normal commands, and since we have `--auth` enabled, we need to do `rs.initiate()` without auth first (auth with keyfile means internal auth only applies to internal replication - external clients still need user auth).\nI'm realizing the localhost exception in MongoDB 6.0 allows unauthenticated connections only when there are no users yet, but the real blocker here is that the readiness probe is trying to ping before the replica set is initialized, and the 1-second timeout is too aggressive for this scenario. The mongosh command is timing out after 1 second, which is the default readiness probe timeout—I need to increase that. But there's a deeper issue: even with a working probe, the StatefulSet will still initialize pods sequentially, and the replica set won't be ready until all three are up. I'm weighing two approaches: either use parallel pod management to start all pods simultaneously and then initialize the replica set, or fix the probe to just check if mongod is listening without requiring replica set initialization, then handle the initialization separately.\n\nActually, `db.adminCommand('ping')` should work on an uninitialized replica set—it's just a connectivity check. The real problem is likely just the 1-second timeout being too short for mongosh to start up. Let me delete the current StatefulSet and increase the readiness probe timeout to something more reasonable. The probe timeout of 1 second is definitely the culprit—I need to bump that to 5 seconds. I'm also thinking through the initialization sequence: with `--keyFile` enabled, the localhost exception still applies for the first admin user creation, so I can use `rs.initiate()` without authentication initially. My approach is to switch to `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` so all three pods start together, fix the probe timeout, then manually initialize the replica set and create users once they're all running. After `rs.initiate()`, the node becomes PRIMARY and I can create users during that window. For the readiness probe, the real issue is that mongosh takes over a second to start while the probe timeout is only 1 second, so I should either increase the timeout to 5 seconds or switch to a simpler TCP socket check that just verifies the port is listening.\n\nThe better approach is to use a TCP socket readiness probe for speed, enable parallel pod management so all three pods start simultaneously, and then run the initialization script once they're all ready. This avoids the complexity of exec probes and lets the StatefulSet ordering happen naturally.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3265,"cache_read_input_tokens":32662,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3265},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"955daefe-f40e-495f-a26d-5eac82682d5f","uuid":"3b412b2f-95ae-434d-b860-5f4b0549373c","request_id":"req_011Cccwor7QBkR7ZKL8KJ8Dn"}
